<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFCE4945B1B50B940" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFCE4945B1B50B940" blockId="56.[791,1383,404,822]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CFCE4945B1A09B911" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[792,1033,514,547]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kitcheneri">Hypsugo kitcheneri</taxonomicName>
may be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CFCE494701DB2B978" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1915" box="[792,946,553,586]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lophurus">H. lophurus</taxonomicName>
, although the bacula of the two are morphologically distinct. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFCEB94D91A8FB9F2" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="distribution">
<caption id="90EB6676FFC36A7CFCEB94D91A8FB9F2" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6397994" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6397994" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6397994/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" targetBox="[175,767,407,820]" targetPageId="56">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFCEB94D91A8FB9F2" blockId="56.[791,1383,404,822]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFCEB94D91DC7B9AB" bold="true" box="[791,967,640,665]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Distribution.</emphasis>
NC, SW &amp; SE Borneo; possibly in extreme N Borneo.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFCEB949E1B4ABF78" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="description">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFCEB949E1B4ABF78" blockId="56.[791,1383,404,822]" lastBlockId="56.[176,1383,828,1492]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFCEB949E1A16B9DA" bold="true" box="[791,1046,711,744]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body ¢. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFC36A7CFB0C949E1B5FB9DA" box="[1264,1375,711,744]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" unit="mm" value="56.0">56 mm</quantity>
, tail c. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFC36A7CFC9F94AB1DD0B83D" box="[867,976,754,783]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" unit="mm" value="41.0">41 mm</quantity>
, ear c. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFC36A7CFBC994AB1AA0B83D" box="[1077,1184,754,783]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
, forearm 35-38 mm. Dorsal pelage of the Red-brown Pipistrelle is rich reddish brown (hairs with black bases); ventral pelage is slightly paler and grayer. Membranes are brown. Ears are short and subtriangular; tragus is broad and curved forward. Skull is moderately large and slightly broadened; rostrum is comparatively elongate; zygomatic arches are moderately thick with distinct postorbital processes; basioccipital pits are deep and distinct. C' is unicuspid; P? is small and intruded, I? has large posterior cusp; lower incisors are weakly or not imbricated; I, is slightly larger than I; and P, is slightly over one-half the area and two-thirds the height of P.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
